      "content": "The expansion of the social safety net over the last decade has created a clear negative link to labor participation rates, as generous benefits like expanded unemployment insurance and expanded SNAP have reduced the financial incentive for many low-income workers to seek employment. Research consistently shows that when the cost of being unemployed or working part-time drops below the cost of full-time work, participation rates stagnate or decline, particularly among single parents and the elderly. This isn't just a statistical correlation; it's a direct economic reality where safety net generosity acts as a disincentive to work, which is why policies that tighten eligibility or reduce benefit duration are often necessary to restore labor market engagement.",
